. S e t 1 : x1; . . . ; xi√Ä1, yj; . . . ; yn a n d y1; . . . ; yj√Ä1, xi; . . . ; xm.
. S e t 2 : x1; . . . ; xi√Ä1, yj√Ä1; . . . ; y1 a n d yn; . . . ; yj, xi; . . . ; xm.
This implies that we can treat each unsigned chromosome Y in two ways, Y ¬º y1; y2; . . . ; yn or Y ¬º yn; yn√Ä1; . . . ; y2; y1.
For two signed chromosomes X ¬º x1; x2; . . . ; xm and Y ¬º y1; y2; . . . ; yn in a genome, a translocation cutting at gene xi√∞1 < i m√û and gene yj√∞1 < j n√û leads to one of the following two sets of chromosomes:
. S e t 1 : x1; . . . ; xi√Ä1, yj; . . . ; yn a n d y1; . . . ; yj√Ä1, xi; . . . ; xm.
. Set 2: x1; . . . ; xi√Ä1, √Äyj√Ä1; . . . ; √Äy1 and √Äyn; . . . ; √Äyj, xi; . . . ; xm.
Again, we can treat each signed chromosome Y in two ways, Y ¬º y1; y2; . . . ; yn or Y ¬º √Äyn; √Äyn√Ä1; . . . ; √Äy2; √Äy1.
Here, none of the four segments cut by the translocation operation is empty. Throughout this paper, we work on this restricted version. The translocation distance between two (signed/unsigned) genomes is the minimum number of translocations used to transform one genome into the other. We use ds√∞A; B√û and d√∞A; B√û to represent the signed translocation distance and unsigned translocation distance, respectively.
The signed translocation problem was first studied in [7]. Lots of algorithms have been developed since then [5], [10], [p1]Ô¨É.Ô¨ÉÔ¨ÉÔ¨ÉÔ¨ÉÔ¨ÉRÔ¨ÉÔ¨ÉÔ¨ÉeÔ¨ÉÔ¨ÉÔ¨ÉcÔ¨É ently, Ozery-Flato and Shamir gave an O√∞n3=2 log√∞n√û√û algorithm in [9]. The translocation distance computation for unsigned genomes was first studied by Kececioglu and Ravi [7]. The problem was proved to be NP-hard by Zhu and Wang in [11]. Kececioglu and Ravi gave a ratio-2 approximation algorithm for computing the translocation distance of unsigned genomes [7]. Cui et al. gave a ratio -1.75 approximation algorithm [4].
In this paper, we present a ratio-1:5 √æ  approximation
algorithm for computing the translocation distance of
unsigned genomes, where  > 0 is any conqstÔ¨ÉaÔ¨ÉÔ¨ÉÔ¨ÉnÔ¨ÉÔ¨ÉÔ¨ÉtÔ¨É.Ô¨ÉÔ¨ÉÔ¨ÉÔ¨ÉFor ratio 1:5 √æ , our algorithm runs in O√∞n2 √æ √∞4√û1:5 log√∞4√û24√û time,
