Example 2. Let the two genomes be

A ¬º f√∞1; 2; 3√û; √∞4; 6; 5; 7√ûg and B ¬º f√∞1; 2; 3√û; √∞4; 5; 6; 7√ûg:

Both A and B contain two chromosomes. See Fig. 1b.

Note that every vertex is incident with either one black

edge and one gray edge or two black edges and two gray

edges. Therefore, the cycle decompositions for G√∞A; B√û are

not unique. Once we have a cycle decomposition for the

breakpoint graph of two unsigned genomes, we can get a

unique breakpoint graph of two signed genomes, that is, we

can assign a sign to each gene in the genomes. Without loss

of generality, we assume that all genes in B are positive.

Therefore, all gray edges in the signed breakpoint graph have the form √∞ih; √∞i √æ 1√ût√û. Given a cycle decomposition of

the unsigned breakpoint graph, we assign the two ending

genes in each chromosome in A as follows: If the ending

gene is at the left ends or at the right ends in both A and B,

then the gene is positive in A; otherwise, it is negative in A.

A positive gene xi corresponds to a pair of vertices √∞xti; xhi √û,

and a negative gene xi corresponds to a pair of vertices

√∞xhi ; xti edges

√û. For √∞ih; √∞i

the rest of the genes xi, we can use the gray √æ 1√ût√û (starting with the ending genes) to

determine if gene xi corresponds to the pair of vertices √∞xti; xhi √û or √∞xhi ; xti√û. Therefore, we can determine the sign of xi. Let us look at Fig. 1b. Suppose the cycle decomposition
of the first genome is f√∞1; 2√û; √∞2; 1√ûg and f√∞2; 3√û; √∞3; 2√ûg. The

genes in the chromosome in B are all positive f√æ1; √æ2; √æ3g.

All the ending genes are also positive in A. Therefore,

gene 1 corresponds to √∞1t; 1h√û. In cycle f√∞1; 2√û; √∞2; 1√ûg, the

gray edge √∞1h; 2t√û is connected to the black edge √∞2t; 1h√û.

Thus, gene 2 corresponds to the pair √∞2t; 2h√û, and the sign of

gene 2 should be positive in A.

3 AN EQUIVALENT TARGET FOR OBTAINING Ratio-1:5 √æ 
To approximate the translocation distance of the unsigned genomes A and B, we always compute the cycle decomposition of G√∞A; B√û to get the assignment of signs to A and B. Let A and B be two unsigned genomes and G√∞A; B√û be the unsigned breakpoint graph. Let Gospt√∞A; B√û be a signed breakpoint graph corresponding to an optimal (among all possible ways of assigning signs to genes) cycle decomposition of G√∞A; B√û such that the unsigned distance d√∞A; B√û ¬º n √Ä N √Ä copt √æ sopt √æ fopt, where copt, sopt, and fopt are the number of cycles, the number of minSP s, and the remaining index in Gospt√∞A; B√û, respectively. The following

lemma shows that keeping the maximum number of 1-cycles is a good strategy:
Lemma 3. We modify Gospt√∞A; B√û as follows: If two vertices in G√∞A; B√û are connected by a black edge and a gray edge, then we reassign the signs of the two genes to obtain a 1-cycle. Assume that c√É, s√É, and f√É are the number of cycles, the number of minSP s, and the remaining index in the resulting breakpoint graph G√És√∞A; B√û, respectively. We have d√∞A; B√û ¬º n √Ä N √Ä copt √æ sopt √æ fopt ¬º n √Ä N √Ä c√É √æ s√É √æ f√É.
Proof. Consider two vertices xi and xi√æ1 that are neighbors in both genomes, and xi and xi√æ1 are not in a 1-cycle in Gospt√∞A; B√û. After reassigning the signs of the two genes to obtain a 1-cycle, we get a new cycle decomposition G0s√∞A; B√û. Let c0, s0, and f0 be the number of cycles, the number of minSP s, and the remaining index in G0s√∞A; B√û, respectively. We will prove that
n √Ä N √Ä copt √æ sopt √æ fopt ! n √Ä N √Ä c0 √æ s0 √æ f0;
that is, G0s√∞A; B√û is also an optimal cycle decomposition. We consider two cases:
1. Only one sign of xi and xi√æ1 is changed. Without loss of generality, assume that the sign of xi is changed. Figs. 2a and 2e show the breakpoint graphs before and after changing the sign of xi. After changing the sign of xi, the black edges √∞r√∞xi√Ä1√û; l√∞xi√û√û and √∞r√∞xi√û; l√∞xi√æ1√û√û are in two different cycles. Thus, we have c0 ¬º copt √æ 1. Moreover, the number of minSP s is not changed or is decreased by one. When the number of minSP s is not changed, the remaining index is also not changed. When the number of minSP s is decreased by one, the remaining index is increased by at most one. Thus, we have sopt √æ fopt ! s0 √æ f0 and n √Ä N √Ä copt √æ sopt √æ fopt ! n √Ä N √Ä c0 √æ s0 √æ f0.
2. The signs of both xi and xi√æ1 are changed. Since we have to change the signs of both xi and xi√æ1 to get the 1-cycle, the gray edge √∞l√∞xi√û; r√∞xi√æ1√û√û must be in Gospt√∞A; B√û. Thus, the two black edges √∞r√∞xi√Ä1√û; l√∞xi√û√û and √∞r√∞xi√æ1√û; l√∞xi√æ2√û√û are in one cycle before changing the signs. Three subcases arise. (See Figs. 2b, 2c, and 2d.) After changing signs, we get the breakpoint graphs illustrated in Figs. 2f, 2g, and 2h, respectively. In Fig. 2f, the number of cycles are increased by two, that is, c0 ¬º copt √æ 2. The number of minSP s is

