component, it must be of the same type as that in Fig. 3a. However, the black edge in C2 that is not √∞r√∞xj√û; l√∞xj√æ1√û√û cannot be in the range ¬Ωxi√Ä1; xj√æ2¬ä. (See Fig. 5a.) Thus, C1 and C2 cannot be in a related component. The case in Fig. 5b is symmetric. Therefore, when st ¬º 1, zout ! st √æ sir. The 2-cycle C2 in Figs. 5a and 5b is called the key 2-cycle. Clearly, any key 2-cycle cannot be a removable cycle for any RS-MSP.
Now, consider the case that st ! 2. Let Ia ¬º xi; xi√æ1; . . . ; xj√Ä1; xj and Ib ¬º yi; yi√æ1; . . . ; yj√Ä1; yj be two of such st S-MSPs. Let Ca and Cb be the key 2-cycles of Ia and Ib, respectively. If Ca and Cb are not identical, then we can conclude that there are at least st isolated 2-cycles outside minSP s and zout ! st √æ sir.
In the rest of the proof, we will show that Ca and Cb
are not identical. For the S-MSP Ia, without loss of generality, assume
that xj > xi. For the S-MSP Ib, let ymin be the minimum of yi and yj, and ymax be the maximum of yi and yj. Ia contains all genes with their values in ¬Ωxi; xj¬ä, and Ib contains all genes with their values in ¬Ωymin; ymax¬ä.
We will show that if Ca and Cb are identical, then ¬Ωymin; ymax¬ä ' ¬Ωxi; xj¬ä. This contradicts the fact that Ia and Ib are two distinct S-MSPs.
Suppose Ca and Cb are identical. Let C√É denote the identical 2-cycle. C√É contains two black edges, where one black edge is √∞r√∞xi√Ä1√û; l√∞xi√û√û or √∞r√∞xj√û; l√∞xj√æ1√û√û, and the other is √∞r√∞yi√Ä1√û; l√∞yi√û√û or √∞r√∞yj√û; l√∞yj√æ1√û√û. Some cases arise. We assume that Ia and Ib are on the same chromosome. The cases that Ia and Ib are on different chromosomes are the same. The following fact is crucial and is repeatedly used in the proof.
Fact 1. Ia contains all genes with their values in the segment ¬Ωxi; xj¬ä, and every gene appears only once.
Case 1. C√É contains two gray edges that are twisted. The possible locations of C√É are illustrated in Figs. 10a, 10c, and 10e. Another case is to reverse the direction of the chromosome in Fig. 10c and is symmetric. In Fig. 10a, the existence of gray edges √∞l√∞xi√û; r√∞xj√æ1√û√û implies that xj√æ1 ¬º xi √Ä 1 or xj√æ1 ¬º xi √æ 1. From fact 1, we can conclude that only xj√æ1 ¬º xi √Ä 1 holds. The existence of gray edge √∞r√∞xj√û; r√∞yi√Ä1√û√û indicates that yi√Ä1 ¬º xj √æ 1 or yi√Ä1 ¬º xj √Ä 1. Again, Fact 1 implies that only yi√Ä1 ¬º xj √æ 1 holds. Similarly, by gray edge √∞l√∞yi√Ä1√û; r√∞yj√û√û, we have yj ¬º yi√Ä1 √æ 1 or yj ¬º yi√Ä1 √Ä 1. However, it is impossible that yj ¬º yi√Ä1 √Ä 1 ¬º xj. (It contradicts the fact that each gene appears once.) Therefore, we have yj ¬º yi√Ä1 √æ 1 ¬º xj √æ 2. By gray edge √∞l√∞xj√æ1√û; l√∞yi√û√û, we have
yi ¬º xj√æ1 √Ä 1 ¬º xi √Ä 2:
